{"/service/ndnp/whi/batch_whi_havarti_ver01/data/sn83045293/00542868764/1927092901/0506.xml":{"full_text":"BANK TRANSACTIONS\nWednesday, Sept. 28, 1927\n$18,832,864\nAll banks reported.\nU. S. Exports Past Six Months at Highest Point Since 1921\nGAIN DESPITE\nWIDESPREAD\nPRICE DROPS\nMotors, Steel, Cotton\nIncrease \u2014F oods\nFalling Off.\nWASHINGTON\u2014 Despite a de\ncline in prices, the total value of\nAmerican exports for the first six\nmonths of the year was the largest\nsince 1921, as shown in a bulletin\non Our World Trade issued today\nby the foreign news department of\nthe Chamber of Commerce of the\nUnited States.\nExports for the first half of the\nyear amounted to more than two\nand a third billion dollars, being 7.2\nper cent larger than a year ago. This\nrecord was accomplished in spite of\nthe fact that the average unit prices\nof 17 out of 20 leading export com\nmodities were lower than a year\nago.\nMajority Products Gained.\n\u201cExports of American finished\nmanufacturers,\u201d says the chamber,\n\u201cexceeded one billion dollars for the\nfirst time since the first half of\n1921, a period of inflated prices.\nNotwithstanding the lower price\nlevel, gains in value among our 50\nleading exports were registered by\n22 out of 33 manufactured products,\nfour out of seven manufactured\nfoodstuffs, four out of five crude\nfoodstuffs, and three out of five raw\nmaterials.\n\u201cSubstantial increases occurred\nin exports of grains, fruits and nuts,\ntextiles, chemicals, machinery and\nvehicles, timber, sawmill products,\n*nd nonferrous metals. Exports of\nmeat, lard and petroleum products\nCell off.\n\u201cThe foreign demand for Ameri\ncan cotton was the heaviest in\nyears. Fourteen-cent cotton \u20146\ncents off last year\u2019s price\u2014found\nforeign markets to the extent of\nnearly five and a quarter million\nbales \u2014a 68 per cent increase over\nlast year\u2019s first-half total.\n\u201cGermany, with six months of\nsteady industrial prosperity, was\nthe largest buyer of our cotton, more\nthan doubling her purchases of last\nyear. Russia, China, Hongkong and\nJapan also greatly increased their\npurchases of cotton. Despite the\ndrop in the price the huge volume\nshipped abroad brought the total\nvalue up to $377,000,000, or $52,000,-\n000 more than last year.\nNew Recond in Motors.\n\u201cForeign demand for American\nautomobiles brought our exports of\ntrucks and passenger cars to new\nrecords. We shipped abroad 54,725\nmotor trucks and buses, not includ\ning electric, 56 per cent more than\na year ago, and 160,000 passenger\ncars, 26 per cent more than in the\nfirst six months of 1926. The value\nof exports of automobiles, parts and\naccessories, except tires, was $212,-\n078,000, nearly 23 per cent higher\nthan last year, setting a new high\nwater mark? for a six-month\u2019s period.\n\u201cDuring this period we exported\n45,833,000 bushels of wheat as com\npared with 27,857,000 a year ago,\nan increase of 65 per cent in vol\nume. The average export price was\n$1.50 a bushel, 3 cents lower than\nlast year, the total value amounting\nto $68,581,000 as against $42,576,000\nIn 1926.\n\u201cWith a decrease of 71 cents a\nbarrel exports of wheat flour made\na 23 per cent gain in value from\n$30,935,000 to $38,189,000. The\nquantity increased from 4,198,000 to\n5,733,000 barrels, or 37 per cent. Ex\nports of coal-tar products almost\ndoubled In value, increasing from\n$5,390,000 to $10,629,000, a gain of\n97 per cent.\nSteel. Machinery Gain.\n\u201cOther substantial increases In\nvalue among our leading exports\nMilwaukee Produce Prices\u2014Corrected Daily\ndairy markets.\nButter\u2014Creamery, fresh, extras, tubs,\n45^4c; extra firsts, 43@44c; firsts, 40@\n42c- seconds, 36@38c; centralized, 88 to\n90 score, 43c; ladles, 38@40c; packing\n\u2022tock No. 1, 25\u00ae37c; off-stock, 15 30c.\nCheese American, full cream, twins,\n26@26%c; daisies, single 26^@27c;\ndouble, 26%c; Young Americas, 26%@\n27c; longhorns, 26*4 @27c; squares, 2<@\n27\u2019/4c. 5-lb. loaves \u2014American, 33@35c;\npimento, S6@3Bc; brick, 34\u00ae36c; Swiss,\n40 43c. Special makes\u2014Brick, fancy,\n25 26c; limburger, winter make, 24\n24%c; Swiss, block, 28\u00ae32c; loaf, 32\u00a9\n38c; imported. Swiss, 48@50c.\n\u2014Fresh-gathered firsts, standard\ncases Included, 34@35c; ordinary firsts,\n\u2022hipers* cases included, 32 @33c; dirties,\ncandled 22@23c; seconds, checks, can\ndied, 20@21c; refrigerators, 2914 @3oc.\nFRUITS.\nApples\u2014Michigan or Wisconsin, per\nbu $1 50@2,00; Western, Jonathans,\n-A\" grade, 2%-in., $2.7 5 @3.00; No. 2,\n$1.75@2.00.\nCrabapples\u2014Hyslops, Siberian, per bu.,\n|2.75@3.00.\nBananas \u2014Per 100 lbs., $6.00 @6.50.\nGrapes\u2014California, 4-basket, seedless,\n$1.75@2.00; Malagas, $1.50@x,85; Tokays,\n$1.90@2.25; Cornishon, $1.75@2.25; Juice\ngrapes. lugs, Zinfandel. $1.60 @1.65;\nMuscat, $1.25 @1.50; Michigan, black\ngrapes. 5-lb. baskets, 28@30c; jumbo\nbaskets, 65@70c.\nLemons \u2014California, per box, $12.00\n12.50.\nGrape Fruit\u2014Florida, per box, $6.50\nLOO.\nLimes \u2014Imported, 100, $3.00 @3.50.\nOranges California, Valencias, per\nbox, as to size and quality, $6.00@9.<5.\nPeaches \u2014Michigan, bushels. Elbertas,\n$3.50@4.00; Colorado, boxes, $1.50@1.60.\nPears California, boxes, $4.00@4 25;\nMichigan. Bartletts, bushel, $3,00@3.50.\nPlums \u2014CaMf., 4-basket crates, $1.25@\n1.50; Michigan, bushel, $1.50@2.50.\nMELONS.\nCantaloupes Colorado, standard\ncrates, $2.50@3.00: fiats, $1.00@1.25;\nhome-grown, crate or bushel. $1.50@2.00.\nBERRIES.\nBlueberries\u2014Wisconsin. 16 qt. cases.\n|3.00@4.50.\nCranberries \u2014Cape Cods. boxes (*4\nbbls.), $6.50@6.75.\nVEGETABLES.\nBeets\u2014Home-grown, doz, bunches, 20\nSTEEL RATE TO\nINDIANAPOLIS\nUNREASONABLE\nWASHINGTON\u2014A report filed\nby Examiner Harry C. Barron with\nthe interstate commerce commission\nfinds that iron and steel rates from\nChicago and the Chicago switching\ndistrict from Gary, Ind., Chicago\nHeights and Joliet, over interstate\nroutes to Indianapolis, should be\nfound unreasonable.\nThe examiner\u2019s report finds that\nreparation should be awarded on\npast shipments to W. H. Holliday\nCo. of Indianapolis, the complain\nant in Docket No. 18,402 and that\nreasonable rates should be pre\nscribed for the future from Joliet,\n111.\nThe commission is asked to pre\nscribe reasonable rates for the fu\nture from Joilet and to award repa\nration on all shipments covered by\nthe complaint.\nFARM EDITORS\nSTUDY METHOD\nOF AIDING SOIL\nLOUISVILLE, Ky.\u2014Methods of\nrevitalizing the soil, which has been\nimpoverished through lack of proper\nfertilization, were discussed today\nat a meeting of leading farm edi\ntors, federal soil experts and com\nmercial fertilizer manufacturers.\nOv^er 100 Attend.\nThe ccnference was called by Dr.\nTait Butler, Memphis, Tenn., edi\ntor of The Progressive Farmer.\nMore than 100 experts are attend\ning.\nMembers of the conference termed\nfailure properly to fertilize land\nfrom year to year a \u201cnational crime\nof soil robbery.\u201d They advocated\nstate and federal education cam\npaigns to induce farmers to buy\nproper soil foods.\nChemical plant foods, it was\npointed out, are only beneficient\nwhen properly used. Soils vary in\nthe amount of various plant food\nelements required. The farm paper\neditors \"were urged to publish arti\ncles on proper fertilization and the\ncommercial companies were asked\nto co-operate in advertising their\nproducts along this line.\nCall Upon Government.\nIn this connection, the govern\nment experts will be asked to work\nout fertilization formulas which are\nnot too technical to be understood\nby the farmers using them.\nThe editors were expected to\nadopt resolutions urging increased\nappropriations for federal and state\nsoil research.\nwere made in the following com\nmodities: Iron and steel plates,\nsheets, skelp and strips, 17 per cent;\nbrass and bronze, 42 per cent; oil\nwell machinery, 42 per cent; pow\ner-driven metal-working machinery,\n25 per cent; gas and fuel oil, 21 per\ncent; sulphur, 42 per cent; automo\nbile tires, 30 per cent; rye, 189 per\ncent; fresh apples, 118 per cent;\noranges, 35 per cent; canned fruits,\n64 per cent, and fish, 35 per cent.\nFood Values Decline.\n.\u201cThe severest declines in value\nwere sustained by foodstuffs, lard\ndeclining 20 per cent; hams and\nshoulders, 41 per cent; bacon, 43 per\ncent, and corn 41 per cent. Agricul\ntural machinery and implements\nwere 12 per cent lower, an improve\nment over the 25 per cent decrease\nin the first quarter.\n\u201cIn quantity exports of corn de\nclined 37 per cent; hams and shoul\nders, 39 per cent; bacon, 35 per\ncent; freight cars, 52 per cent, and\nharvesters and binders, 52 per\ncent.\u201d\nAbsolute zero in science is the\npoint at which objects are entirely\ndevoid of heat. This point is 459.4\ndegrees below Fahrenheit.\n@2sc; per bushel, tops off, 75c@51.00.\nBrussels Sprouts\u2014Calif., qt., 28 30c.\nCabbage Home-grown, bushel, 50 0\n60c; per ton, $12.00@14.00.\nCarrots Home-grown, doz. bunches,\n20@25c; per bushel, tops off, 65@75c.\nCauliflower Home-grown, bushel,\n75c@51.50.\nCelery\u2014Michigan, boxes, 50@60c; Hy\nball, crate, 75@85c; home-grown, doz.\nbunches, 50@60c.\nCelery Root \u2014Home-grown, doz as to\nsize, 40 50c.\nCucumbers \u2014Hot house, doz., 50@75c;\noutdoor, bushel. SI.OO @1.50.\nEgg Plant \u2014Home-grown, bushels, 75c\n@sl.oo.\nEndive\u2014Home-grown, bushel, SI.OO\n1.25.\nGarlic\u2014California, per lb., 12 16c.\nGreen Onions\u2014Home-grown, doz. bchs.,\n25 35c.\nGreen Feas Colorado, large crate.\n$6.00@6.50.\nHorseradish Southern, root, per lb\u201e\nfancy, t.hick, 22%@25c.\nLeek Home-grown, per bunch, 12\nstalks, 10@15c.\nLettuce \u2014Leaf\u2014Home-grown, doz., 20\n@2sc.\nLettuce\u2014Head\u2014Western, crate, $2.00\n@3.00: home-grown, box or bushel. 50c\n@sl.oo.\nMushrooms \u2014Per lb., No. 1, 1-lb. boxes,\nSo@9oc; buttons, 50@60c.\nOnions Yellow, sacks, per 100 lbs..\n$1.50@1.75; Spanish, crate, $2.50@2.75.\nParsley Home-grown, dozen small\nbunches, 15@20c.\nParsnips Home-grown, bu., washed,\n$1.00@1.25.\nPeppers\u2014Home-grown, bushel, 75c\nSI.OO.\nPotatoes Kansas, Nebraska, sacked\ncobblers, per 100 lbs., $1.85@2.00; Min\nnesota or Wisconsin, $1.75@1.90; Early\nOhios, $1.65@1.75; Idaho, rurals, $2.00@\n2.25.\nPumpkins\u2014Home-grown, doz., SI.OO\n1.50.\nRadishes Home-grown, doz. bchs.,\noutdoor. 25 30c.\nSpinach\u2014Home-grown, bushel, SI.OO\n1.25.\nString Beans Home-grown, bushel,\nwax, $1.75@2 00; green, $2.00@2.25.\nSquash Home-grown, doz., $1.50\n2.00.\nSweet Potatoes Jerseys, hampers.\n$1.75@2.00; Virginia barrels. $3.50@3.75.\nTomatoes\u2014Home-grown, out-door, bu.,\n50 75c.\nThe Leader Financial Page\nFOURTEEN\nCARELESSNESS\nOF FARMER HIT\nBY PYRENE HEAD\nNEW YORK\u2014Lower production\ncosts and not higher prices are need\ned by the American farmer to free\nhim from difficulties, Walter Bauer,\npresident of Pyrene Manufacturing\nCo., declared here recently, assert\ning \u201cthe American farmer is the\nmost careless property owner in the\nworld,\u201d and that as a result fire in\nsurance companies were faced with\na serious problem.\nNinetysix farms burn up every\nday of the year at a total annual\ncost of $150,000,000, Mr. Bauer de\nclared. This figure is based on in\nsurance statistics and does not take\ninto consideration about 25 per cent\nof the farms not insured.\nDecline to Renew Policies.\nMany large stock fire insurance\ncompanies are declining to renew\nfire policies on rural properties ow\ning to their unfavorable loss experi\nence in the last few years, Mr.\nBauer said. The companies are not\ncanceling existing business, but are\ndiscontinuing their protection as\npolicies mature, except as a matter\nof accomodation.\nThis throws a tremendous burden\non the farm mutual fire insurance\ncompanies of the middle west now\ndoing their best to educate the far\nmer through advertising campaigns.\n\u201cThirtyfive per cent of farm fires\nare from unknown causes,\u201d declared\nMr. Bauer, \u201cor, in other words, from\ncarelessness. Anyone traveling\nthrough the agricultural districts\nknows how careless the American\nfarmer is.\nMachinery Left in Weather.\n\u201cHe will leave a brand new trac\ntor out in all weather, hoping that\neverything will turn out all right\nand that it won\u2019t rust in its most\nimportant parts. He does not look\nafter his property and takes little\nor no protection against fire, al\nthough his property is many miles\nfrom an organized fire department.\n\u201cThe farmer does not realize that\neven if he is insured his loss prob\nably will far exceed the money he\ncan collect. On the average the ac\ntual loss of value from fire exceeds\nthe insurance by-50 per cent.\n\u201cThe farmer does not realize\nwhen he joins a farm mutual asso\nciation that he pays indirectly for\nthe carelessness of other farmers.\nThese losses, of course, keep up the\ncost of agriculture in this country\nand discourage those who turn to\nthe land for a living.\n\u201cIf the farmer could be induced\nto use the ordinary care taken in\nbusiness to keep down costs, he\nwould be able to make a more prof\nitable living.\nLoss $150,000,000 Yearly.\n\u201cIn the five years, 1919 to 1923,\ntotal insured farm losses for the en\ntire country were only $141,000,000.\nIn 1926 the cost of farm fires was\n$150,000,000.\n\u201cOne big factor seems to be the\nincrease in spontaneous combustion\nlargely due to increased production\nof hay. This could be offset by get\nting the hay properly dried before\nputting it into the barns.\n\u201cLosses have hit in particular the\ndairy farmers, where the size of the\nbarns has increased greatly to take\ncare of increasing production. These\nlarger barns possess a greater at\ntraction for lightning and should\nhave, but don\u2019t most' of the time,\nlightning rods.\nCanada\u2019s Loss Lessened.\n\u201cA remarkable contrast is shown\nin Canada\u2019s farming districts where\nlosses by fire have been falling each\nyear since 1922. In 1926 Canada\u2019s\nfire losses were 31 per cent below\n1922. The Canadian government\nhas done great work in educating\nthe farmers and encouraging them\nto form their own fire fighting\nforces with suitable up-to-date ap\nparatus.\u201d\nTurnips\u2014Per bushel, tops off, 65@75c.\nPRODUCE MARKETS.\nBeans Navies, choice, hand picked,\nper 100 lbs. (sacks included), $5.00@\n5.25; Red Kidney, $7.00 @7.50; Brown\nSwedish, $6.00@6.50; Lima Beane. Cali\nfornia, $7.50 @B.OO.\nBees Wax Choice to fancy, per lb.,\nbright, 28@30c; dark, 23@25c;, and\ndown to 20c.\nHoney Comb, per cases, 25 1-lb. sec\ntions, fancy, white. $4.75@5.00; dark,\n$4.25@4.50; mixed sells at around $4.25.\nExtracted, lb., white clover, 11 12c;\namber, 9@loc.\nPeas \u2014Per 100 lbs (new, 100-lb. sacks)\ngreen, $3.00; Scotch, $3.25; white, $3.50;\nmarrow fats, $4.50; split peas, yellow,\n$5.75@6.00; green. $5.75@6.00.\nPop Corn\u2014Quotable per 100 lbs., ears,\n$3.00 3.50; shelled, do, $4.00 5.00;\nbroken, poor, less.\nTallow\u2014Prime, 9%@10c; No. 1, solid,\n6%@7c: No. 2, 554 @6c; cakes, **6@Bc;\nrough, 2% 3c.\nWool\u2014Medium, per lb., 80 32c; low,\n28@30c.\nMEATS AND POULTRY.\n(Poultry and veal prices, furnished by\nMilwaukee Poultry Dealers\u2019 Assn.)\nPigeons Ola flyers, live, per doz.,\n$1.25@ 1.50; dead. $1.00@1.25; squabs,\nlive, per doz., $2.00@2.50; dressed, fat,\n$3.00@3.50; thin, poorly dressed, sl.oo@\n1.50.\nPoultry\u2014Live\u2014Fowls, 4 lbs. and over,\n23c; under 4 lbs., 16c; roosters, old or\nstaggy young, 16c; springers, 24c; me\ndium springers. 23c; leghorn springers,\n21c; broilers, 23c; black chickens, 16c;\nturkeys, young, 25c; old Toms, 18c;\nducks, general run. 20c; heavy, white,\n22c; geese, old, 14c; young. 19c; Guinea\nhens, per doz., young, $5.00@6.00.\nVeal \u2014Calves, 50 to 60 lbs., fair kid\nneys, 16c; 60 to 70 IDs., choice, meaty,\n18c; 70 to 80 lbs., good kidneys. 20c;\nSO to 90 lbs., cnolce. 20c; 90 to 110 lbs.,\nfancy, 21c; 90 to 110 lbs., extra fancy,\n22c; overweight calves. thin, bony,\nrough-meated poor Kidneys. poorly\ndressed or off-stock. 80 to 175 lbs., as to\nquality and condition, 10@14c.\nHides\u2014Calf, green. 17c; cured, 18c;\nkips,, green. 12c; cured, 13c; cow, green,\n7c; cured, 8c; bull, green, sc; cured, 6c;\ndeacons, green, each, 60c; slunk, green,\neach, 25c; horse No. 1, green, each $3.50;\ndo, No. 2 greea, each $2.25; pelts, green,\neach 50c@51,50.\nMILWAUKEE, THURSDAY, SEPTEMBER 29, 1927\nTENDING BUSINESS\nAlthough further evidence of\nbusiness revival has appeared in the\nlast few weeks, it is hardly suf\nficient to indicate whether the in\ncrease in activity has been more or\nless pronounced than is usual at\nthis time of year, according to the\nsurvey of the Guaranty Trust Co.,\nNew York.\nIn some respects the trend dur\ning the last fortnight has been\nrather disappointing. The iron and\nsteel industry, for example, after\nMACHINE TOOL\nTRADE GAINS\nNEW YORK\u2014lnquiries for ma\nchine tools were in larger volume\nduring September and forecast a\ngain in business for the autumn\nwhich should make up for the de\nficiencies of the summer months,\nAmerican Machinist reports. New\nequipment just brought out by ma\nchinery manufacturers is attracting\nwidespread attention. In Detroit\nthe automobile makers are watch\ning developments closely and much\nbusiness is known to be pending.\nChicago and Cincinnati are work\ning on leads furnished by the exhi\nbitions. In the east buying slowed\ndown somewhat during the past\nweek, but activity is expected to\nresume in October.\nAsk Lower Rates\nFrom Minneapolis\nMINNEAPOLIS Minneapolis\nshippers yesterday asked the inter\nstate commerce commission hold\nings here to cut the grain freight\nrate from Minneapolis to the south\nand west. The shippers asked that\nproportional rates on wheat from\nMinneapolis to St. Louis be cut\nfrom 20 to 17% cents a hundred\nweight, corn 18% to 16 cents, and\nflour from 20 to 17% cents.\nChicago Livestock\nCHICAGO Cattle\u2014Receipts, 10,000;\nfed steers strong to unevenly higher,\ngenerally highest of season; good market\non all other classes; heavy fed steers up\nto $16.25; several loads $15.75@16.15;\nheavy western grassers up to ?13.40;\nmost rangers $11.25 down; stockers and\nfeeders largely $8.00@9.25; qualified\nlight yearlings up to $10.00: bulls very\nscarce; heavy sausage offerings $7.00\n7.35; vealers steady at $16.50@17.00.\nSheep\u2014Receipts, 12,000; fat lambs\nopening fairly active; most early sales\ngood natives at $13.50, strong to 15c\nhigher, wet fleeces considered; several\nloads up to $13.75; asking around $14.00\nfor best good to choice rangers held\naround $14.15; none sold; very few buck\nlambs, 110-130 pounds, SI.OO @12.00;\nculls $9.50@10.50; sheep strong; bulk\nfat ewes $5.50@6.50; feeding lambs firm;\ngood to choice 63-67-pouid finishers,\n$13.00@13.50; heavies down to $12.50;\nchoice lightweights held around $14.00.\nHogs (soft or oily hogs and roasting\npigs excluded): Receipts. 11,000; market\ngenerally steady to strong; heavyweight,\n250-350 pounds, mediun^ to choice, $10.25\n@11.65; mediumweight, 200-250 pounds,\nmedium to choice, $11.10@11.80; light\nweight, 160-200 pounds, common to\nchoice, $10.75@11.80; light lights, 130-\n160 pounds, common to choice, $9.40\n11.40; packing sows, smooth and rough,\n$9.00@10.15: slaughter pigs, 90-130\npounds, medium to choice, $8.50@10.50.\nSlaughter cattle and calves: Steers,\n1,500 pounds up, good and choice, $13.00\n@16.25; steers, 1,100-1,500 pounds,\nchoice, $15.25@16.25; good, $12.50@15.40;\nsteers, 1,100 pounds down, choice, $15.00\n@16.00; good, $12.00@15.25; medium,\n$9.00@12.75; common, $6.75@9.00; light\nyearling steers and heifers, good and\nchoice, 850 pounds down, ?11.00@15.50;\nheifers, good and choice, 850 pounds up,\n$9.50@13.75; common and medium, all\nweights, $6.75@10.75; good and choice,\n$7.50@10.50; common and medium, $6.00\n@7.50; low cutter cutters, $5.00@6.00;\ncalves, medium to choice, $7.00@11.00;\nvealers, cull to choice, $7.00 @17.50;\nfeeder and stock cattle, steers, common\nto choice, $7.00@10.50.\nSlaughter sheep and lambs: Light\nand handyweight, 92 pounds down, me\ndium to choice, $12.35@ 14.15; cull and\ncommon, all weights. $9.50@12.35; ewes,\nmedium to choice, $3.75@6.50; cull and\ncommon, $1.50@4.00; feeding lambs,\nrange stock, medium to choice, $12.00\n14.00.\nFOREIGN EXCHANGE.\nNEW YORK\u2014Foreign exchange closed\nirregular. Demand sterling, 4.86*4, up\n1-16; francs, .0 39 2 54, up .000054: Ure,\n.0 545 54 belga, .1392; marks. .237954,\noff .0001*4; Mantreal, $1.0015675.\nChicago Cash Grain\nCHICAGO\u2014Wheat\u2014No. 2 red, $1.3 254\nNo. 2 red. $1.3154 @1.31%; No. 3 hard,\n$1.30%. Corn\u2014No. 2 yellow, 96%@97c;\nNo. 3 yellow, 93% @94c; No. 4 yellow,\n92c; No. 5 yellow, 90c; No. 6 yellow, 88\n@B9c; No. 3 mixed, 92%c; No. 5 mixed,\n88c; No. 6 mixed, 88@8854c; No. 3 white.\n93 0 94c; No. 5 white, 88@89c; No. 6\nwhite, 87 54 @88c; sample grade, 82@87c.\nOats\u2014No. 2 white, 50*4 @s2c; No. 3\nwhite, 4854 0 51c; No. 4 white, 48@48*4c;\nBarley\u201476 0 88c. Rye\u2014No. 2, 9854\n9 8 54c; No. 3. 96c. Timothy\u2014s2.7o 3.45.\nClover\u2014Jsl\u00df.so @26.50.\nMilwaukee Livestock\nHOGS\u2014Receipts, 2,600; 10 25c lower.\nPrime heavy and butchers,\n250 lbs. up $10.25@11.40\nFair to best light butchers.\n200 to 240 lbs 10.75@11.75\nFair to good lights, 160-190. 11.n0@11.70\nFresh light lights, 130-160.. 9.50@10.50\nFair to select packers 9.50@10.00\nRaugh and greasy 8.50 0 9.25\nPigs and light lights 8.00 0 9.75\nStags 7.75 0 8.75\nGovernment throwouts 1.00 6.00\nCATTLE\u2014Receipts, 700; steady.\nSteers, good to choice $10.50013.00\nMedium to good 9.00 010.50\nFair to medium B.oo@ 9.00\nCommon 5.000 7.00\nHeifers, good to choice 7.00@ 9.50\nMedium to good 6.000 7.75\nFair to medium 6.000 7.00\nCommon to fair 5.00 0 6.00\nCows, good to choice 7.50 0 8.00\nMedium to good 6.250 7.00\nFair to medium 5.7506.25\nCutters 5.00 0 5.50\nCanners 4.500 4.85\nButchers\u2019 bulls 7.000 7.25\nBologna bulls 6.25@ 7.00\nMilkers and springers, good\nto choice (common sell\nfor beef) 60.000125.00\nCALVES\u2014Receipts. 1,000; steady.\nGood to choice. 100 lbs. up. 516.50017.00\nFair to good 15.50016.50\nThrowouts 7.00@10 00\nSHEEP\u2014Receipts, 300; steady.\nLambs, good to choice ewes\nand wether 13.00@13 25\nLambs, fair to good ewes\nand wether 12.25@12.75\nLambs, light bucks, fair to\ngood 12 00012.50\nLambs heavy bucks 8,00010.00\nLambs, culls, all grades.... 7.00 0 9.00\nLight ewes 5.00\u00ae 6.00\nHeavv ewes 3.50 0 4.00\nEewes. cull and canners I.oo@ 3.00\nBucks 3.00 3.50\nreporting sos August the first in\ncrease in activity in five months,\nhas recently experienced a mild set\nback both in demand and in operat\ning schedules, together with a meas\nure of price weakness.\nThis month the most definite pro\ngress has been reported by whole\nsale dealers, who have been less af\nfected than retail concerns by the\nunseasonably warm weather that\nhas prevailed over wide areas.\nThe outlook for trade during the\nautumn season is essentially the\nsame as a month ago. Mercantile\nconditions remain generally favor\nable to a continuance of good busi\nness, without indicating a likeli\nhood of any marked expansion.\nOn the financial side, the con\ntinued low level of money rates\npoints to the same conclusion. There\nwas an expected upturn in open\nmarket rates at the middle of this\nmonth, due in part to the demands\noccasioned by quarterly tax pay\nments and in part to the expecta\ntion of withdrawals of funds for\ncrop-moving and other seasonal pur\nposes.\nThe prompt resumption of pre\nvious low levels, however, combined\nwith a very moderate increase in\nthe amount of \"\u201call other\u201d (mainly\ncommercial) loans and discounts by\nreporting member banks of the fed\neral reserve system during the first\ntwo weeks of September, suggests\nthat the demand for funds for com\nmercial purposes has not yet as\nsumed large proportions.\nFROST HURTS\nBADGER CROPS\nThe weather for week ending\nyesterday was not favorable to\ncrops in Wisconsin, according to\nW. P. Stewart, federal meteorolo\ngist stationed here.\nFrost occurred over practically\nthe entire state on the 23rd, with\nfreezing temperatures in central\nand northern counties. There was\nconsiderable damage to corn, to\nbacco and truck, and plant growth\nwas stopped over the greater part\nof the state.\nModerate to heavy general rains\nfell on the 25th, 26th and 27th.\nFall plowing made good progress\nbefore the rains and the sowing of\nwinter grains is well advanced.\nThe tobacco harvest is nearing com\npletion.\nMuch corn has not matured. The\nfilling of silos 'is well advanced.\nLittle seed corn has been picked.\nPotatoes are being dug and cab\nbage harvested; yields are lair.\nTruck, apples and sugar beets are\nreported fair to good.\n9,800,000 Tons of\nCoal Dug in Week\nThe total production of bitumin\nous coal in the United States during\nthe week ended Sept. 24, estimated\nby the National Coal Assn, from\npreliminary car loading reports, was\nabout 9,800,000 net tons.\nRevised reports covering loadings\nof soft coal during the week ended\nSept. 17 proved the total tonnage\nto be lower than was expected from\nthe original figures received. The\ntotal output for that week, as re\nported by the United States Bureau\nof Mines, was 9,648,000 net tons.\nFor the week ended Sept. 10 figures\nfrom the same source show a total\nof 8,980,000 net tons.\nN.Y. Stock Market Closing Prices!\nClose.\nWednesday\nAllied Chemical 159\nAllis-Chalmers 114\nAm. Beet Sugar 18%\nAm. Can 61\nAm. Car and Foundry 101%\nAm. and Foreign Power 29%\nAm. Locomotive 106%\nAm. Smelting 171%\nAm. Sugar 90\nA. T. and T 175%\nAm. Tobacco B 149y 2\nAm. Woolen 22%\nAnaconda Copper 47%\nA. T. and S. F.... 190%\nBaldwin Locomotive 248%\nBaltimore and Ohio 119%\nBethlehem Steel 60\nCalifornia Petroleum 22%\nCanadian Pacific 185\nCase Threshing 256\nCentral Leather 19%\nCerro de Pasco 64%\nChesapeake and Ohio 204\nChicago Great Western 15%\nC. M. and St. Paul 16%\nC. M. and St. Paul pfd 32%\nChicago and North Western.... 93%\nChi., Rock Isl. and Pacific 107%\nChile Copper 35%\nChrysler Motor 57%\nColorado Fuel 78%\nConsolidated Gas 117%\nCorn Products 59\nCrucible Steel 88%\nDu Pont De Nemours 328\nElec. P. and L. Ctfs 28%\nErie Railroad 63%\nGeneral Asphalt 72%\nGeneral Cigar 67%\nGeneral Electric 133%\nGeneral Motors 259%\nGoodrich B. F 82%\nGreat Northern pfd 101\nGreat Northern Ore Ctfs 25%\nGreene Cananea Mining 75%\nHudson Motors 78%\nIllinois Central 135%\nIndian Refining 10%\nInspiration Copper Mining 18\nInternational Harvester 221\nInternational Paper 56%\nKansas City Sou 63%\nKansas City Sou. pfd. 72\nAUTUMN PICKUP\nIN STEEL TO BE\nLATE THIS YEAR\nCHICAGO\u2014The customary au\ntumn revival in the steel industry\nwill come later than usual this\nyear. Thus far it has failed to ap\npear; in fact, steel production thus\nfar this month has fallen below 7\nthat of August. Prices also show\nfurther weakening.\nMills Running 60 Per Cent.\n\u201cSteel works in Pittsburgh and\nnearby districts are now running\nat about 60 per cent of capacity,\nagainst 65 per cent for the first\nhalf of this month,\u201d The Iron Age\nsays in its mid-week review.\n\u201cThe Chicago district is holding\nclose to the 60 per cent rate of the\nlast two weeks. The Steel corpora\ntion\u2019s average for all districts is\nslightly under 55 per cent. For the\nfirst time in more than three\nmonths, a decline is recorded in the\nfinished steel composite price.\n\u201cRail business is coming forward\nat about the same time as last year\nand in a number of dises for larger\namounts, as heavier rails are being\ntaken. Several large automobile\ncompanies have just put out in\nquiries for their fourth quarter\nsteel, but purchases are likely to be\nless than for that period last year.\nConstruction work still makes the\nbest show\u2019ing on the score of vol\nume.\u201d\n\u201cIn both demand and price, the\ndrift in finished steel has been\ndownward in the last week,\u201d The\nIron Trade says. \u201cContinued in\ndifference on the part of tonnage\nusers, still closer buying by small\nconsumers and unsettled prices\nhave resulted in one of the light\nest buying weeks this year. Pur\nchases by farm implement manufac\nturers are partially an orffset to\nthe more slender orders from other\nlines.\u201d\nMoto Industry Slackens.\nSlackening also appears in the\nautomobile industry. August pro\nduction is placed at 303,040 cars\nand trucks by the department of\ncommerce, compared with 263,406\nin July, and 422,294 in August, Ipst\nyear. For the eight months this\nyear, output was 2,593,154 vehicles,\nagainst 3,082,569 in the same period\nlast year.\n\u201cAutomobile sales are receding in\naccord with the seasonal trend aft\ner an August and early September\nvolume that established new rec\nords for several companies,\u201d Auto\nmotive Industries says. \u201cOn the\nw 7 hole, however, the situation can\nbe considered fairly satisfactory\nfor a majority of the producers.\nThe year\u2019s sales so far have been\nhigh for a good many companies,\nboth large and small.\n\u201cTwo or three of the largest fac\ntories have suffered and perhaps\nan equal number of the smaller\nones. The distribution of sales has\nbeen unusually spotty and the\nprofit situation is much the same.\u201d\nChicago Bridge Co.\nGets Export Order\nCHICAGO\u2014The Chicago Bridge\nIron works has a large export\norder involving 9,000 tons of tank\nworks from the Anglo-Mexican Pe\ntroleum Co., Ltd., (Royal Dutch-\nShell), which includes fabrication\nand erection of more .than 50 tanks,\nalso miscallaneous plate work in\nconnection with the construction of\na new refinery on the Island of\nAruba, Dutch West Indies.\nClose.\nWednesday\nKennecott Copper 73%\nKresge S. S 72%\nLehigh Valley 103%\nLou. and Nash 151%\nMarland Oil 35\nMiami Copper 14%\nMissouri, Kansas and Texas 45\nMissouri Pacific 54%\nMontgomery Ward 81%\nNational Biscuit 146\nNational Lead 123\nNevada Cons./ Copper 15%\nNew York Central 166%\nN. Y. N. H. and Hart 52%\nNorthern Pacific 95\nPacific Gas and Elec 43%\nPan Amn. Pet. and Trans 50%\nPennsylvania R. R 66%\nPeoples Gas Chicago 158\nPure Oil 26%\nRay Cons. Copper 15%\nReading 114%\nRepublic Iron and Steel 64\nReynolds Tobacco \u201cB\u201d 149\nRoyal Dutch 45%\nSears, Roebuck 76%\nShell Union Oil 25%\nSinclair Cons. Oil 17\nSouthern Pacific 121\nSouthern R. r 132%\nStandard Dil of Califocrnia.... 53%\nStandard Oil of New Jersey.... 39%\nStudebaker 57%\nTennessee Copper 8%\nTexco 51%\nTexas and Pacific 98%\nTimken Roller Bearing 114%\nTobacco Products 96%\nTranscontinental Oil 7%\nUnion Oil of California 42\nUnion Pacific 188%\nU. S. Rubber 56%\nU. S. Steel 146%\nU. S. Steel pfd 136%\nVanadium 51%\nVa.-Carolina Chemical 12%\nWabash 69\nWabash pfd. A 96%\nWestinghouse E. and M 83%\nWillys-Overland 15\nYellow Truck 34\nPAGE FOURTEEN\nHUGE POTATO\nFARM YIELDS\n210 BU. ACRE\nASHLAND, Wis.\u2014An average\nyield of 210 bushels of potatoes\nper acre is reported by the Peter\nFox Sons Co. farm, near San\nborn. The farm contains 230\nacres and some acres are yield\ning as high as 400 bushels and\nothers as low as 100, according\nto A. M. Fox, manager of the\nfarm.\nThe venture was an experi\nment in wholesale potato grow\ning, and it was more successful\nthan had been anticipated, Fox\nstates. The total yield on the\nfarm will approximate 48,300\nbushels with a valuation, at cur\nrent market prices, of more than\n$50,000.\nDigging the potatoes started\nabout two weeks ago, and will\nprobably be completed by Oct. 5,\nit w 7 as said.\nLOWER CABLES\nCAUSE DROP IN\nWHEAT FUTURES\nCHICAGO\u2014Lower cables result\ned in wheat futures opening %c to\n%c lower here today. Corn opened\n%c higher to %c lower, and oats\n%c to %c lower.\nWeather Hits Harvest.\nWeather conditions in Canada\nand our northwest were unsettled\nand not favorable to completion of\nwheat harvest. The export demand\nfor wheat must show a material in\ncrease if prices of this grain are to\ngo higher, it was said in the pit.\ntn the past few days a large number\nof spreads on wheat and corn have\nbeen closed, strengthening wheat\nand depressing corn.\nRain Worse Than Frost.\nRains were general again today\nthroughout the corn belt. Although\nfrost is being delayed, traders are\nslowing up in their sales as experts\nforecast more damage to the crop\nfrom rain than frost would have\ndone.\nReceipts of new oats at various\npoints are much smaller than last\nyear, and the news has tended to\nfirm this market recently.\nProvisions opened lower.\nChicago Grain Opening.\nWheat \u2014September, off %c; De\ncember, off %c; March, off %c.\nCorn \u2014September, up'%c; Decem\nber, off %c; March, unchanged.\nOats\u2014September, off %c; Decem\nber, off %c.\nAmerican Ice Pays\n50 Cents on Common\nNEW YORK\u2014A quarterly divi\ndend of 50 cents a share on the\nnew common stock was declared to\nday by American Ice Co., placing\nit on an annual dividend basis of\n$2. The old stock, split four for\none, paid $8 a year.\nCash Grain\nBarley\nEasier and 1c lower. Receipts smaller.\nSlow malting- and shipping demand.\nHeavy wanted. Choice to fancy, 48 to\n50 lb. test, quotable at 85@86c; fair to\ngood, 44 to 47 lb. test, 76@85c; light\nweight, 40 to 43 lb. test, 75@80c; feed,\n70 75c.\nCorn\nEasier and 1c lower with futures. Re\nceipts smaller and chiefly on sale. Good\ndemand, shippers and industries' buying.\nNo. 3 yellow quotable at 1%-@l%c under\nDecember. No. 3 white quotable 2@3c\nunder December. No. 3 mixed 3@4c un\nder December price, as to moisture and\ncolor.\nOats\nQuiet, firm with futures but reduced\nbasis. Receipts light. Heavy wanted.\nDemand fair from shippers. No. S\nwhite quotable 3c over December to\nl%c under.\nRye\nEasier and l%c lower with reduced\nbasis. Receipts light. Good demand\nfrom shippers. No. 1 sold at 98c, I%@\n2c over December.\nWheat\nFirm to 1c higher with futures. Re\nceipts light. Good demand from ship\npers.\nN. Y. Liberty Bonds\nNEW YORK\u2014Liberty bonds closed:\n3%5, $101.14; first 4%5, $103.5; second\n4%5, $100.16; third 4%5, $100.29; fourth\n4\u20194\u00ae, $103.30; treasury 4%5, $113.29;\ntreasury 4s $109.3; treasury 3145, $108.3;\ntreasury 3%5, $lOl.B.\nMILWAUKEE HAY MARKET.\nNo. 1 timothy, $16.00 @17.00; No. 2\ntimothy, $15.00@16.00; No. 3 timothy,\n$12,00@ 14.00; No. 1 mixed, $15.00@16.00;\nNo. 2 clover, mixed, $14.00@ 15.00; sam\nple hay, $10.00@12.00; marsh feeding\n$ll.OO @12.00; packing, SIO.OO 10.50; rye\nstraw, SIO.OO 10.50; oat straw. slo.oo@\n10.50.\nNORTHWESTERN MARKETS.\nMINNEAPOLIS Wheat. September,\n$1.27; December, $1.29@1.29%; March,\n$1.32. Oats, December, 46c. Barley,\nSeptember, 7214 c; December, 72%c. Rye,\nDecember, 9014 c. Flax. September,\n$2.14\u20194: December, $2.18\u20194; October,\n$2.14%.\nWINNIPEG\u2014Wheat, October, $1.37;\nDecember. $1.31% @1.31% May, $1.35%\n@1.35%.\nTOLEDO SEED MARKET.\nTOLEDO Clover, imported, cash,\n$14.25: October, $15.85; December, $14.25;\nDecember. domestic, $16.00; March,\n$16.20. Aisike, cash. $14.80; December,\n$14.90; January, sls 05. Timothy, cash,\n$1.60; December, $1.65; March, $1.85.\nSPECIAL NEW YORK STOCKS.\nElectric Boat 17%\nFisk Rubber 16%\nGeneral Outdoor Advertising.. 57%\nHupp 18%\nInternational Nickel 69%\nM., K. and T., pfd 106%\nMissouri Pacific pfd 103\nMack Truck 108%\nNorth American 58%\nNash Motors M\nPackard Motors 42%\nWoolworth 184%\nMiddlewest Utilities 113\nSubmarine Boat d%\nNational Dept. Stores 23%\nGeneral American Tank 58\nKelly Tires 28%\nSnubbers 38\nWednesday\u2019s Grain Changes\nBarley\u2014lc lower.\nCorn\u2014lc lower.\nOats\u2014Firm; quiet.\nRye\u2014l%c lower.\nWheat\u2014Firm to 1c up.\nPRICES FIRM\nON EXCHANGE,\nRAILS LEADING\nNEW YORK Traders who sold\non the expectation that brokers\u2019\nloans iwould show an unprecedented\nincrease were reassured by liquida\ntion and re-entered the market to\nday, with the result that prices\nturned firm with rails the feature.\nC. O. Climbs Skyward.\nChesapeake Ohio rose to new\nterritory at 2:05%, up 1%. Chesa\npeake corporation also spurted more\nthan a point to a new peak at 78.\nNew Haven, \u201cWestern Maryland and\na long list of other carriers gained.\nSteels, Motors, Oils Firm.\nGeneral Motors old stock opened\nlower at 259, but quickly snapped\nto 261% The new was up a point at\n130%. Utilities, Steels, Motors and\nOils moved narrowly, but prices\nwere firm.\nOpening prices included:\nUnited States Steel, 147%, up\nGeneral Motors, 259, off Gen\neral Motors new, 129%, up\nMontgomery Ward, 82%, up 1;\nNash, 92%, up 1%; Sears, Roebuck,\n76%, up United States Rubber,\n56%, off American Can, 61%,\noff Baldwin, 248%, up Beth\nlehem Steel, 60; Chrysler, 57%.-\noff\nDividend Declared\nBy Moe-Bridges\nAt a meeting of the board of di\nrectors of the Moe-Bridges Co. held\nat its office recently the 32nd con\nsecutive quarterly dividend was\ndeclared, payable Oct. 1, on its out\nstanding 8 per cent cumulative class\nA preferred stock, to stockholders\nof record as of Sept. 30, 1927.\nNew York Cotton\nNEW YORK\u2014The cotton futures mar\nket opened 14 to 26 points lower. Octo\nber 21.53; December 21.76; January\n21.75; March 22.12; May 22.27; July\n22.14.\nNew York Produce\nNEW YORK\u2014Flour, dull and un\nchanged. Pork, quiet; mess, $33.00.\nLard, easier; mid-west spot, $12.80\n12.90. Sugar, raw, easier; spot, 96 test,\ndelivered duty paid, $4.77; refined, dull;\ngranulated, $5.90@6,10. Coffee, Rio No.\n7 on spot, 13%c; Santos No. 4, 18%\n19c. Tallow, steady; special to extra,\nB@B%c. Hay, dull; No. 1, $1.10; No. 3.\n85@95c; clover, 80c@$1.05. Dressed\npoultry, firm; turkeys, 20@60c; chick\nens, 20@39c